'Tala', colorway 'Mobesk' in wool with silk accents as a possible design for this southern California home. Tala isÂ one of the ancient traditional rhythmic patterns of stressed and unstressed beats played on a percussion instrument in South Asia. The pattern for 'Tala' is derived from an image of rare ice balls that formed in Lake Michigan and floated to Chicago's shore this winter. A rare phenomenon dependent on extreme cold, wind, and small pieces of ice continuously rolling along the top of the lake. For myself the pattern when abstracted has an interesting non symmetrical rhythm that reminds me of the experimental composer John Cage's prepared piano works. A similar sound found in the traditional music of South Asia. Finding that jumping off point to develop a concept is always intriguing. I am always interested in how designers and artists think. How they extrapolate more tangible ideas from abstract perceptions, sometimes based on pure form and feeling, and then design functioning products that expresses those perceptions.
.
